Demo for Python to R spatial script conversion

Finding geometry that occupies the largest area within another geometry.

library(sf)
## Linking to GEOS 3.9.0, GDAL 3.2.2, PROJ 7.2.1; sf_use_s2() is TRUE
library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)
library(scales)

# Use `sf` North Carolina simple feature dataset
nc <- system.file("shape/nc.shp", package="sf") |>
      st_read()
## Reading layer `nc' from data source 
##   `/home/bruno/R/x86_64-pc-linux-gnu-library/4.1/sf/shape/nc.shp' 
##   using driver `ESRI Shapefile'
## Simple feature collection with 100 features and 14 fields
## Geometry type: MULTIPOLYGON
## Dimension:     XY
## Bounding box:  xmin: -84.32385 ymin: 33.88199 xmax: -75.45698 ymax: 36.58965
## Geodetic CRS:  NAD27
# A shape
circle <- c(-79.59, 35.69) |>
          st_point(2L) |>
          st_sfc(crs = st_crs(nc)) |>
          st_buffer(dist = 80000L) |>
          st_as_sf()

# County intersecting with circle
inter <- st_intersects(nc, circle, sparse = FALSE) |>
          which()

# County with the largest area intersecting with circle
predom <- local({
  inter <- st_intersection(nc, circle)
  inter$CNTY_ID[which.max(st_area(inter))]
})
## Warning: attribute variables are assumed to be spatially constant throughout all
## geometries
nc$circle_relation <- "NOTOUCHING"
nc$circle_relation[inter] <- "TOUCHING"
biggy <- which(nc$CNTY_ID == predom)
nc$circle_relation[biggy] <- "BIGTOUCHING"

percent(as.numeric(st_area(nc$geometry[biggy]) / st_area(circle)), accuracy = 0.1)
## [1] "9.9%"

Now lets see it on a plot.

#  G G Plot plot plot 
ggplot() +
  geom_sf(data = nc, aes(fill = circle_relation)) +
  geom_sf(data = circle, fill = NA, color = "darkgreen") +
  scale_fill_viridis_d() +
  theme(legend.position = "bottom") +
  labs(fill = "Touching the circle?")

csv_out <- tempfile()
nc_out <- nc
class(nc_out) <- class(data.table())
fwrite(nc_out[,!names(nc_out) %in% "geometry", with = FALSE], csv_out)

Extract information from an elevation raster and compute terrain

library(bcmaps)
library(raster)
## Loading required package: sp
# A point in Skeena
cold_circle <- 
  c(-127.103, 55.674) |>
  st_point(2L) |>
  st_sfc(crs = st_crs(4326)) |>
  st_buffer(dist = 30000L) |>
  st_as_sf()

# It uses raster package function raster to read in the tif file
elev_vrt <- cded(aoi = cold_circle, ask = FALSE)
## checking your existing tiles for mapsheet 93m are up to date
elev <- raster(elev_vrt)

# It can be transformed into a simple feature, but I think working directly with the raster layer is fine and more efficient.
# ?raster::rasterToPolygons
# ?stars::read_stars
# ?sf::st_as_sf

# Aspect and slop rasters, rough surfaces
terr <- terrain(elev, opt = c("slope", "aspect"), neighbors = 8L)
plot(terr)
